                            <h1>
                            Beware of Pride
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <div class="byline" id="">
				<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p3" class="">President Ezra Taft Benson</p>
			</div>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            
                            <blockquote class="intro dontHighlight">
                                        <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/ezra-taft-benson?lang=eng">
                                                        <img id="talkPhoto" src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/leaders/ezra-taft-benson-10.jpg" alt="Ezra Taft Benson" class="img-decor">
                                                    </a>
                                        
                                        
                                        
                                    </blockquote>
                            <h2>Beware of Pride</h2>
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">03239_000_003</span>
			<div class="figure">
				<img src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/gospel-library/magazine/ensignlp.nfo:o:1dac.jpg" alt="President Ezra Taft Benson">
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p4" class="">My beloved brethren and sisters, I rejoice to be with you in another glorious general conference of the Church. How grateful I am for the love, prayers, and service of the devoted members of the Church throughout the world.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p5" class="">May I commend you faithful Saints who are striving to flood the earth and your lives with the Book of Mormon. Not only must we move forward in a monumental manner more copies of the Book of Mormon, but we must move boldly forward into our own lives and throughout the earth more of its marvelous messages.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p6" class="">This sacred volume was written for us&mdash;for our day. Its scriptures are to be likened unto ourselves. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/19.23?lang=eng#22" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 19:23</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p7" class="">The Doctrine and Covenants tells us that the Book of Mormon is the &ldquo;record of a fallen people.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/20.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 20:9</a>.) Why did they fall? This is one of the major messages of the Book of Mormon. Mormon gives the answer in the closing chapters of the book in these words: &ldquo;Behold, the pride of this nation, or the people of the Nephites, hath proven their destruction.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/moro/8.27?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moro. 8:27</a>.) And then, lest we miss that momentous Book of Mormon message from that fallen people, the Lord warns us in the Doctrine and Covenants, &ldquo;Beware of pride, lest ye become as the Nephites of old.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/38.39?lang=eng#38" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 38:39</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p8" class="">I earnestly seek an interest in your faith and prayers as I strive to bring forth light on this Book of Mormon message&mdash;the sin of pride. This message has been weighing heavily on my soul for some time. I know the Lord wants this message delivered now.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p9" class="">In the premortal council, it was pride that felled Lucifer, &ldquo;a son of the morning.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/24.12-15?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 24:12&ndash;15</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/76.25-27?lang=eng#24" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 76:25&ndash;27</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/4.3?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 4:3</a>.) At the end of this world, when God cleanses the earth by fire, the proud will be burned as stubble and the meek shall inherit the earth. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/12.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 12:5</a>, <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/25.1?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 25:1</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/29.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 29:9</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/js-h/1.37?lang=eng#36" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">JS&mdash;H 1:37</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/mal/4.1?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mal. 4:1</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p10" class="">Three times in the Doctrine and Covenants the Lord uses the phrase &ldquo;beware of pride,&rdquo; including a warning to the second elder of the Church, Oliver Cowdery, and to Emma Smith, the wife of the Prophet. (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/23.1?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 23:1</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/25.14?lang=eng#13" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 25:14</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/38.39?lang=eng#38" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 38:39</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p11" class="">Pride is a very misunderstood sin, and many are sinning in ignorance. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/3.11?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 3:11</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/6.18?lang=eng#17" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 6:18</a>.) In the scriptures there is no such thing as righteous pride&mdash;it is always considered a sin. Therefore, no matter how the world uses the term, we must understand how God uses the term so we can understand the language of holy writ and profit thereby. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/4.15?lang=eng#14" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 4:15</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/1.3-7?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 1:3&ndash;7</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/5.61?lang=eng#60" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 5:61</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p12" class="">Most of us think of pride as self-centeredness, conceit, boastfulness, arrogance, or haughtiness. All of these are elements of the sin, but the heart, or core, is still missing.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p13" class="">The central feature of pride is enmity&mdash;enmity toward God and enmity toward our fellowmen. <span class="emphasis">Enmity</span> means &ldquo;hatred toward, hostility to, or a state of opposition.&rdquo; It is the power by which Satan wishes to reign over us.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p14" class="">Pride is essentially competitive in nature. We pit our will against God&rsquo;s. When we direct our pride toward God, it is in the spirit of &ldquo;my will and not thine be done.&rdquo; As Paul said, they &ldquo;seek their own, not the things which are <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a>&rsquo;s.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/philip/2.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Philip. 2:21</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p15" class="">Our will in competition to God&rsquo;s will allows desires, appetites, and passions to go unbridled. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/38.12?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 38:12</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/12.30?lang=eng#29" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 12:30</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p16" class="">The proud cannot accept the authority of God giving direction to their lives. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/hel/12.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Hel. 12:6</a>.) They pit their perceptions of truth against God&rsquo;s great knowledge, their abilities versus God&rsquo;s priesthood power, their accomplishments against His mighty works.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p17" class="">Our enmity toward God takes on many labels, such as rebellion, hard-heartedness, stiff-neckedness, unrepentant, puffed up, easily offended, and sign seekers. The proud wish God would agree with them. They aren&rsquo;t interested in changing their opinions to agree with God&rsquo;s.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p18" class="">Another major portion of this very prevalent sin of pride is enmity toward our fellowmen. We are tempted daily to elevate ourselves above others and diminish them. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/hel/6.17?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Hel. 6:17</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/58.41?lang=eng#40" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 58:41</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p19" class="">The proud make every man their adversary by pitting their intellects, opinions, works, wealth, talents, or any other worldly measuring device against others. In the words of C. S. Lewis: &ldquo;Pride gets no pleasure out of having something, only out of having more of it than the next man. &hellip; It is the comparison that makes you proud: the pleasure of being above the rest. Once the element of competition has gone, pride has gone.&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">Mere Christianity,</span> New York: Macmillan, 1952, pp. 109&ndash;10.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p20" class="">In the pre-earthly council, Lucifer placed his proposal in competition with the Father&rsquo;s plan as advocated by Jesus <a class="no-link-style" href="http://jesuschrist.lds.org/">Christ</a>. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/4.1-3?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 4:1&ndash;3</a>.) He wished to be honored above all others. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/24.13?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 24:13</a>.) In short, his prideful desire was to dethrone God. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/29.36?lang=eng#35" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 29:36</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/76.28?lang=eng#27" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 76:28</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p21" class="">The scriptures abound with evidences of the severe consequences of the sin of pride to individuals, groups, cities, and nations. &ldquo;Pride goeth before destruction.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/prov/16.18?lang=eng#17" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Prov. 16:18</a>.) It destroyed the Nephite nation and the city of Sodom. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/moro/8.27?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moro. 8:27</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ezek/16.49-50?lang=eng#48" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ezek. 16:49&ndash;50</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p22" class="">It was through pride that Christ was crucified. The Pharisees were wroth because Jesus claimed to be the Son of God, which was a threat to their position, and so they plotted His death. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/11.53?lang=eng#52" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 11:53</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p23" class="">Saul became an enemy to David through pride. He was jealous because the crowds of Israelite women were singing that &ldquo;Saul hath slain his thousands, and David his ten thousands.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/1-sam/18.6-8?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Sam. 18:6&ndash;8</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p24" class="">The proud stand more in fear of men&rsquo;s judgment than of God&rsquo;s judgment. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/3.6-7?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 3:6&ndash;7</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/30.1-2?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 30:1&ndash;2</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/60.2?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 60:2</a>.) &ldquo;What will men think of me?&rdquo; weighs heavier than &ldquo;What will God think of me?&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p25" class="">King Noah was about to free the prophet Abinadi, but an appeal to his pride by his wicked priests sent Abinadi to the flames. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/17.11-12?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 17:11&ndash;12</a>.) Herod sorrowed at the request of his wife to behead John the Baptist. But his prideful desire to look good to &ldquo;them which sat with him at meat&rdquo; caused him to kill John. (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/14.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 14:9</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/mark/6.26?lang=eng#25" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mark 6:26</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p26" class="">Fear of men&rsquo;s judgment manifests itself in competition for men&rsquo;s approval. The proud love &ldquo;the praise of men more than the praise of God.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/12.42-43?lang=eng#41" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 12:42&ndash;43</a>.) Our motives for the things we do are where the sin is manifest. Jesus said He did &ldquo;always those things&rdquo; that pleased God. (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/8.29?lang=eng#28" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 8:29</a>.) Would we not do well to have the pleasing of God as our motive rather than to try to elevate ourselves above our brother and outdo another?</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p27" class="">Some prideful people are not so concerned as to whether their wages meet their needs as they are that their wages are more than someone else&rsquo;s. Their reward is being a cut above the rest. This is the enmity of pride.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p28" class="">When pride has a hold on our hearts, we lose our independence of the world and deliver our freedoms to the bondage of men&rsquo;s judgment. The world shouts louder than the whisperings of the Holy Ghost. The reasoning of men overrides the revelations of God, and the proud let go of the iron rod. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/8.19-28?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 8:19&ndash;28</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/11.25?lang=eng#24" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 11:25</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/15.23-24?lang=eng#22" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 15:23&ndash;24</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p29" class="">Pride is a sin that can readily be seen in others but is rarely admitted in ourselves. Most of us consider pride to be a sin of those on the top, such as the rich and the learned, looking down at the rest of us. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/9.42?lang=eng#41" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 9:42</a>.) There is, however, a far more common ailment among us&mdash;and that is pride from the bottom looking up. It is manifest in so many ways, such as faultfinding, gossiping, backbiting, murmuring, living beyond our means, envying, coveting, withholding <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/topic/gratitude/">gratitude</a> and praise that might lift another, and being unforgiving and jealous.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p30" class="">Disobedience is essentially a prideful power struggle against someone in authority over us. It can be a parent, a priesthood leader, a teacher, or ultimately God. A proud person hates the fact that someone is above him. He thinks this lowers his position.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p31" class="">Selfishness is one of the more common faces of pride. &ldquo;How everything affects me&rdquo; is the center of all that matters&mdash;self-conceit, self-pity, worldly self-fulfillment, self-gratification, and self-seeking.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p32" class="">Pride results in secret combinations which are built up to get power, gain, and glory of the world. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/hel/7.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Hel. 7:5</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/ether/8.9,16,22-23?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ether 8:9, 16, 22&ndash;23</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/5.31?lang=eng#30" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 5:31</a>.) This fruit of the sin of pride, namely secret combinations, brought down both the Jaredite and the Nephite civilizations and has been and will yet be the cause of the fall of many nations. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/ether/8.18-25?lang=eng#17" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ether 8:18&ndash;25</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p33" class="">Another face of pride is contention. Arguments, fights, unrighteous dominion, generation gaps, divorces, spouse abuse, riots, and disturbances all fall into this category of pride.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p34" class="">Contention in our families drives the Spirit of the Lord away. It also drives many of our <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/2003/05/the-importance-of-the-family?lang=eng">family</a> members away. Contention ranges from a hostile spoken word to worldwide conflicts. The scriptures tell us that &ldquo;only by pride cometh contention.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/prov/13.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Prov. 13:10</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/prov/28.25?lang=eng#24" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Prov. 28:25</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p35" class="">The scriptures testify that the proud are easily offended and hold grudges. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/16.1-3?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 16:1&ndash;3</a>.) They withhold <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/general-conference/2005/10/forgiveness?lang=eng">forgiveness</a> to keep another in their debt and to justify their injured feelings.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p36" class="">The proud do not receive counsel or correction easily. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/prov/15.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Prov. 15:10</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/amos/5.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Amos 5:10</a>.) Defensiveness is used by them to justify and rationalize their frailties and failures. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/3.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 3:9</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/6.30-59?lang=eng#29" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 6:30&ndash;59</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p37" class="">The proud depend upon the world to tell them whether they have value or not. Their self-esteem is determined by where they are judged to be on the ladders of worldly success. They feel worthwhile as individuals if the numbers beneath them in achievement, talent, beauty, or intellect are large enough. Pride is ugly. It says, &ldquo;If you succeed, I am a failure.&rdquo;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p38" class="">If we love God, do His will, and fear His judgment more than men&rsquo;s, we will have self-esteem.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p39" class="">Pride is a damning sin in the true sense of that word. It limits or stops progression. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/12.10-11?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 12:10&ndash;11</a>.) The proud are not easily taught. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/15.3,7-11?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 15:3, 7&ndash;11</a>.) They won&rsquo;t change their minds to accept truths, because to do so implies they have been wrong.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p40" class="">Pride adversely affects all our relationships&mdash;our relationship with God and His servants, between husband and wife, parent and child, employer and employee, teacher and student, and all mankind. Our degree of pride determines how we treat our God and our brothers and sisters. Christ wants to lift us to where He is. Do we desire to do the same for others?</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p41" class="">Pride fades our feelings of sonship to God and brotherhood to man. It separates and divides us by &ldquo;ranks,&rdquo; according to our &ldquo;riches&rdquo; and our &ldquo;chances for learning.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/6.12?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 6:12</a>.) Unity is impossible for a proud people, and unless we are one we are not the Lord&rsquo;s. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/18.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 18:21</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/38.27?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 38:27</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/105.2-4?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 105:2&ndash;4</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/7.18?lang=eng#17" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 7:18</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p42" class="">Think of what pride has cost us in the past and what it is now costing us in our own lives, our families, and the Church.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p43" class="">Think of the repentance that could take place with lives changed, marriages preserved, and homes strengthened, if pride did not keep us from confessing our sins and forsaking them. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/58.43?lang=eng#42" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 58:43</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p44" class="">Think of the many who are less active members of the Church because they were offended and their pride will not allow them to forgive or fully sup at the Lord&rsquo;s table.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p45" class="">Think of the tens of thousands of additional young men and couples who could be on missions except for the pride that keeps them from yielding their hearts unto God. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/10.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 10:6</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/hel/3.34-35?lang=eng#33" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Hel. 3:34&ndash;35</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p46" class="">Think how temple work would increase if the time spent in this godly service were more important than the many prideful pursuits that compete for our time.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p47" class="">Pride affects all of us at various times and in various degrees. Now you can see why the building in Lehi&rsquo;s dream that represents the pride of the world was large and spacious and great was the multitude that did enter into it. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/8.26,33?lang=eng#25" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 8:26, 33</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/11.35-36?lang=eng#34" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 11:35&ndash;36</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p48" class="">Pride is the universal sin, the great vice. Yes, pride <span class="emphasis">is</span> the universal sin, the great vice.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p49" class="">The antidote for pride is humility&mdash;meekness, submissiveness. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/7.23?lang=eng#22" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 7:23</a>.) It is the broken heart and contrite spirit. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/9.20?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 9:20</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/12.19?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 12:19</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/20.37?lang=eng#36" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 20:37</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/59.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 59:8</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ps/34.18?lang=eng#17" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ps. 34:18</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/isa/57.15?lang=eng#14" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Isa. 57:15</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/isa/66.2?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Isa. 66:2</a>.) As Rudyard Kipling put it so well:</p>
			<div class="figure">
				<div class="stanza" id="">
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">The tumult and the shouting dies;</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">The captains and the kings depart.</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Still stands thine ancient sacrifice,</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">An humble and a contrite heart.</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Lord God of Hosts, be with us yet,</span>
	  </div>
					<div class="line" id="">
	    <span class="emphasis">Lest we forget, lest we forget.</span>
	  </div>
				</div>
				<div class="citationInfo" id="">
					<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p56" class="">(<span class="emphasis">Hymns,</span> 1985, no. 80.)</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p57" class="">God will have a humble people. Either we can choose to be humble or we can be compelled to be humble. Alma said, &ldquo;Blessed are they who humble themselves without being compelled to be humble.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/32.16?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 32:16</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p58" class="">Let us choose to be humble.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p59" class="">We can choose to humble ourselves by conquering enmity toward our brothers and sisters, esteeming them as ourselves, and lifting them as high or higher than we are. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/38.24?lang=eng#23" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 38:24</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/81.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 81:5</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/84.106?lang=eng#105" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 84:106</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p60" class="">We can choose to humble ourselves by receiving counsel and chastisement. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/jacob/4.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Jacob 4:10</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/hel/15.3?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Hel. 15:3</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/63.55?lang=eng#54" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 63:55</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/101.4-5?lang=eng#3" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 101:4&ndash;5</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/108.1?lang=eng#0" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 108:1</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/124.61,84?lang=eng#60" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 124:61, 84</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/136.31?lang=eng#30" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 136:31</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/prov/9.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Prov. 9:8</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p61" class="">We can choose to humble ourselves by forgiving those who have offended us. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/13.11,14?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 13:11, 14</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/64.10?lang=eng#9" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 64:10</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p62" class="">We can choose to humble ourselves by rendering selfless service. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/2.16-17?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 2:16&ndash;17</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p63" class="">We can choose to humble ourselves by going on missions and preaching the word that can humble others. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/4.19?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 4:19</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/31.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 31:5</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/48.20?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 48:20</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p64" class="">We can choose to humble ourselves by getting to the temple more frequently.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p65" class="">We can choose to humble ourselves by confessing and forsaking our sins and being born of God. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/58.43?lang=eng#42" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 58:43</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/27.25-26?lang=eng#24" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 27:25&ndash;26</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/5.7-14,49?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 5:7&ndash;14, 49</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p66" class="">We can choose to humble ourselves by loving God, submitting our will to His, and putting Him first in our lives. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/11.11?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 11:11</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/13.33?lang=eng#32" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 13:33</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/moro/10.32?lang=eng#31" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moro. 10:32</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p67" class="">Let us choose to be humble. We can do it. I know we can.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p68" class="">My dear brethren and sisters, we must prepare to redeem Zion. It was essentially the sin of pride that kept us from establishing Zion in the days of the Prophet <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/joseph-smith/">Joseph Smith</a>. It was the same sin of pride that brought consecration to an end among the Nephites. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/4-ne/1.24-25?lang=eng#23" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">4 Ne. 1:24&ndash;25</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p69" class="">Pride is the great stumbling block to Zion. I repeat: Pride <span class="emphasis">is</span> the great stumbling block to Zion.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p70" class="">We must cleanse the inner vessel by conquering pride. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/6.2-4?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 6:2&ndash;4</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/23.25-26?lang=eng#24" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 23:25&ndash;26</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p71" class="">We must yield &ldquo;to the enticings of the Holy Spirit,&rdquo; put off the prideful &ldquo;natural man,&rdquo; become &ldquo;a saint through the atonement of Christ the Lord,&rdquo; and become &ldquo;as a child, submissive, meek, humble.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/3.19?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 3:19</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/13.28?lang=eng#27" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 13:28</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1989/05/beware-of-pride.p72" class="">That we may do so and go on to fulfill our divine destiny is my fervent prayer in the name of Jesus Christ, amen.</p>
		
                            
                            
                            
